monstrating how writers, illuminators, and policy-makers used English saints (including St Edmund) to re-envision the bonds between ancient spiritual purity and contemporary conditions. Treating history and ethical practice as inseparable, poets such as Osbern Bokenham, Henry Bradshaw, and John Lydgate reconfigured England's history through its saints, engaging with contemporary concerns about institutional identity, authority, and ethics. Cynthia Turner Camp is an Assistant Professor of English at the University of Georgia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChristian hagiographyxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aChristian hagiographyxHistory, To 1500. 0aChristian saintsxEngland. 0aChristian saintszEngland. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Saxon saints.  aEthics.  aHenry Bradshaw.  aHistory writing.  aInstitutional identity.  aJohn Lydgate.  aLate medieval England.  aOsbern Bokenham.  aPrecedent.  aSpiritual "golden age".08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311143132140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204466640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782044666423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782044666/original  a978-3-11-143132-1  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles